In Terraform (.tf files), a variable block is used to define input variables, which allow you to customize your configurations without hardcoding values. Here's the basic syntax and some examples:

ðŸ”§ Basic Syntax
hcl
Copy
Edit
variable "variable_name" {
  type        = <type>
  description = "Description of the variable"
  default     = <default_value>  # Optional
}
âœ… Example 1: String variable with default
hcl
Copy
Edit
variable "region" {
  type        = string
  description = "AWS region"
  default     = "us-west-2"
}
âœ… Example 2: Number variable
hcl
Copy
Edit
variable "instance_count" {
  type        = number
  description = "Number of EC2 instances"
  default     = 2
}
âœ… Example 3: List variable
hcl
Copy
Edit
variable "availability_zones" {
  type        = list(string)
  description = "List of availability zones"
  default     = ["us-west-2a", "us-west-2b"]
}
âœ… Example 4: Map variable
hcl
Copy
Edit
variable "tags" {
  type = map(string)
  default = {
    Environment = "dev"
    Owner       = "team-x"
  }
}
How to Use a Variable
In your Terraform configuration, you use the variable like this:

hcl
Copy
Edit
provider "aws" {
  region = var.region
}